  						<table border='0' cellpadding='3' cellspacing='0' width='92%'>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>THE DARKNESS AND THE BALANCE IV--A POWER WITHIN</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><p><b>Chapter 4—A Power Within</p></b>

<p> Though Kithicor wasn’t far, the trip took quite some time because Zarx and Kozo were bickering all the way.  Finally Helfgar broke in. </p>

<p> “Listen, if you two don’t stop we’ll just leave you here and you can carry on alone.” </p>

<p> “Well we don’t need the gnome.  He’s small, dirty, and a waste.” </p>

<p> Kozo had had enough.  His hands lit up with mana and he incanted some words. </p>  

<p> Zarx took a step toward him but his legs were like tree trunks.  He moved so slowly that Kozo simply stepped back to avoid him.  It was though he were walking through a thick soup with heavy weights tied to him.  He grew very angry as he listened to Kozo. </p>

<p> “Listen Dark Elf.  I come of my own free will if you have a problem with that perhaps you should consider your plight.  I can drop you hear and we will carry on without you or…..”</p>

<p> He didn’t get a chance to finish.  His body was overcome with shock.  Pain seared his eyes and faces.  He couldn’t move or feel any part of his body.  He stared in shock.  Ndarye’s tone was soft but firm. </p>

<p> “Make no move upon my race Gnome!  Release him now!” </p>

<p> Gaan drew his axe and stood next to Kozo.  Kozo recovered the use of his limbs and his hands lit up again.  Gaan spoke with a slight crack in his voice. </p>

<p> “You elves are not God’s gift to this world and if it must be, you shall fall here or I shall die in the effort.” </p>

  <p> Zarx had drawn his sword, albeit, slowly.  Helfgar’s pleas for peace were ignored but he refused to be drawn into such an immature quarrel.  Suddenly the talking stopped.  Movement among the party stopped.  Helfgar looked at each person individually.  They were motionless except for their eyes.  All in shock and wondering what had happened.  Zeryl’s voice pierced the silence. </p>

<p> “I grow tired of this inconsequential bickering.  Zarx you carry in your blood the great genetics of the Knights of Hate, and you have betrayed that blood for a great cause.  Not so you can quarrel with a little gnome.  Do not bring shame to yourself or your race in this fashion.  We all share the same goal.  And to destroy what you have started is both stupid and foolish.  Kozo has brought great power with him which can be of much use on this quest.  Bring yourself to a prudent understanding of what must be and let us finish what we have begun in peace.  Otherwise we shall not prevail.” </p>

<p> The entire group stared at Zeryl in shock as once again they could move.  He had shown something they had not seen in him before.  The crown on his head seemed to glow as he had spoken as well and none of them questioned the power that resided within.  As they began to set out again,  silence overtook them, but Zarx was more convince than ever of the truth of his beliefs, and he knew he had to face the facts and obstacles ahead. </p>

<p> “I apologize Kozo.  You have come only to help and that help is both recognized and appreciated.” </p>

<p> “No offense taken.  We gnomes are resilient we are.  But I have come to find the man I seek. And find him I will before I join you.  When I have found him, I will undertake this great mission you are on.” </p>

<p> “Very well then.” </p>

<p> They carried on in silence until they reached Kithicor’s edge. </p>


<p> The dark god of hate laughed out loud.  What concern he had of defeat left him as he watched the mortals quarrel. </p>

<p> “If they travel much longer together, they will kill each other and the darkness will be ushered in without opposition.  That wouldn’t be any fun at all.”  </p>

<p> When Zeryl interceded, his thoughts changed though.  The power he seemed  to have to persuade and reunify this small coalition was disturbing.  Perhaps he should just end Zeryl’s life now.  Perhaps there was something to this prophecy of that idiot Nidus.  He recalled Zeryl’s banishment and marking.  The people tried to kill him three times but something…something miraculous spared him.  His concern returned again with the thought that maybe there was something special about this Dark Elf after all. </p>


<p> The foreboding entrance to Kithicor loomed ahead. </p>

<p> “Everyone draw your weapons.” </p>   

<p> The group stepped into the forest.  The silence seemed all too eerie.  </p>

<p> “There is something here.  Be prepared” </p>

<p> Zeryl seemed to prick as he spoke.  The walked about a half a mile into the forest on their way to High Pass and Zarx was the first to notice.  </p>

<p> “Great God of Darkness!!” </p>

<p> Undead corpses loomed on the dark horizon.  They ambled slowly up a hill toward the party.  And something hideous walked in the center of the mass. </p>

<p> “Good golly there must be thousands of them!” </p>

<p> “Well we came for action let us to work shall we?”

<p> Helfgar called forth a shamanic spirit.  Zarx was covered in a flash of fire after Kozo canted a few words.  </p>

<p> “May the gods of this world protect us.” </p>

<p> Zarx spoke no more words but rushed the undead horde.  He was a dark flash as he swung toward the beast in the center.  Kozo provided much needed fire power that seemed to turn most of the what it touched to ash.  Helfgar and his pet were barely touched.  </p>

<p> “This is no challenge to us!” </p>

<p> Zeryl became focused on the beast in the center.  Though the undead which surrounded it was not a challenge, the beast seemed to exude some strange power.  He watched and entered the mind of the beast………</p>

<p> --You know your god is going to fall—</p>

<p> --Ahh, the one who is chosen, well Zeryl you and your band of hearty brethren shall not pass nor shall you succeed.  I am Karn, the demon of the dead.  You should not have come—</p>

<p> --Karn is it, powerful I suppose?— </p>

<p> --You have no idea—</p>

<p> --Then why do you follow a god that we shall bring down—</p>

<p> Zeryl even smiled at his own pretension.  This comment seemed to anger the beast and he watched as the creature swung a huge club at Zarx, who barely dodged the blow.  </p>

<p> --Oh yes Karn, your god will not survive and you will not make it from this forest alive—</p>

<p> Kozo was screaming. </p>
 
<p> “Zeryl!!! What is Brelious’s name are you doing?” </p>

<p> Zeryl’s eyes were closed.  He smiled at the question and continued. </p>

<p> --You realize Karn, you have no power.  What you do is simply a dictation of he who has sent you.  You really are nothing—</p>

<p> The creature became outraged.  It flailed clumsily around in anger.  Zarx easily hit it as Zeryl seemed to be distracting it.  Ndarye had her hands full as the horde began to surround her and Kozo.  Zeryl snapped from his trance for  a brief moment and raised his hands as sparks flew from them.  The undead horde stared at him and just stood still.  Kozo and Ndarye went back to work</p>

<p> --Zeryl…..—</p>

<p> This was not Karn’s Voice.  This was another voice.  A voice of emmense power.  Zeryl’s body quaked at the sound. </p>

<p> --Bah!! If you cannot even listen to me how can you dethrone me or my god!!??— </p>

<p> The voice seemed to laugh.  And zeryl drew his focus back to the creature.  </p>

<p> --What are you? And what are you trying to do??— </p>

<p> --I am the follower of the darkness and I am going to bring it to your world!— </p>

<p> Zeryl felt a surge of pain rush through his brain and he lost connection with the creature.  He let mana fly from his fingers in random directions.  Hitting some undead and coming very close to emulating Kozo in chaotic and painful mana.  </p>

<p> “What the hell are you doing?” </p>

<p> Kozo ducked out of the way before any real damage was done and peeped around the corner in time to see Zeryl fall to the ground.  Most of the undead had been cleared away but the creature remained and it was focused now…focused on Zarx.  It battered him with a fury of blows.  Zarx fell to the earth.  His sword dropped from his hand.  Helfgar shot ice waves at the creature to no avail.  The creature was intent.  Kozo jumped out from behind the tree and his body lit up.  Helfgar turned to see the blinding light and ducked out of the way.  Ndarye finished mumbling her spell and Zarx stood up, but the light was blinding and he ducked into a brush.  The creature become focused on Kozo as the light lit the forest as it had never seen.  </p>

<p> “LUMINOSO DIO!!” </p>

<p> The blast was huge.  Kozo was knocked to the ground and the blast melted the skin from the creature.  It rambled on as a skeleton though much more unstable than before.  Ndarye saw her chance and incanted a spell of her own.  Red sparks flew from her hands.  The bones of the creature began to crumble and it fell to the earth in big chunks. </p>

<p> Kozo recovered slowly and opened his eyes to a vision of a Dark Elf standing above him with his hand extended. </p>  

<p> “You saved me little one.  For that I owe you more than gratitude.” </p>

<p> “Bah!  I am a wizard that’s what I do.” </p>

<p> “That was quite a blast.” </p>

<p> “Well ya still gotta control it better than that.  Of course I have worse but to use it now would mean certain doom for a lot of people even me. No control.” </p>

<p> Zeryl stood up and Kozo left Zarx and went over to him. </p>

<p> “You almost blasted me!!  Whose team are you on anyway!?” </p>

<p> “Enough good Kozo.  My mind tires of you sniveling.  I was not myself. Something….something..entered me.  I was not in control.” </p>

<p> “Entered you?? Like youre possessed?” </p>

<p> “Yes like that.  That would not be a good thing.” </p>

<p> Kozo stepped back and pulled out his scroll.  He read some words and looked back at Zeryl.  He stared in awe. </p>

<p> “You are this person.  The one I am looking for.  Come to save this world.  Yet you tell me nothing of this???” </p>

<p> “No one knows if I am or not.  They have their beliefs but we must go and see Sir Vislin in High Keep.  That was a weak display of our advisary’s power I can assure you.” </p>

<p> The party regrouped and set off for High Keep.  Their quest had finally begun and they had leapt the first hurdle.  Many more would follow. </p>
 </font></td>
	</tr>
